segments.text: in Fort Worth.
What is today's date?
The 16th of August.
I'd like to ask you first if you will donate this tape and the material on this tape to Texas A&M University Oral History Collection.
I'd be very happy to donate this tape and the contents of it to Texas A&M University.
Great.
Now let's start out with
Where and when you were born?
You were born in 1912 right here in Fort Worth.
Could you tell me about your parents?
Yes.
My father was a very hardworking individual.
He pursued most of his, all of his adult life in the industrial supply business.
And in 1932, he came at the request of his sister, Mrs. Charles F. Adams,
and helped her run her business, which was left in her laps by the death of her husband, Charles Francis Adams.
And my mother was a descendant from German parentage.
Her mother and father both came directly from Germany to the United States.
they came separately and they met in South Bend, Indiana and came to Fort Worth with a group of German families.
They actually came in a wagon train from South Bend, Indiana to Fort Worth and her parents, her father was in the brick
He built it very, very close to the Trinity River.
And in a very severe flood, I guess in the early 1900s, the brickyard was washed away.
But not before he had furnished the bricks to build the original Swift & Company and Armour & Company packing plants.
Really?
Which were in Fort Worth and really established Fort Worth as a great packing house center.
And his brick plant was washed away.
When was this, the turn of the century?
I guess it was in the early 1900s.
I'm not real sure when the first of the Swifton Company and the Armoring Company packing house plants were built.
they have in the past few years have started to be torn down.
The debris and the partially demolished Swifton Company plant is still standing out on north side Fort Worth.
And it burned after it had been closed down and then it was demolished.
But we went out two, three years ago and retrieved some of the bricks, some of the original bricks
and keep them as mementos of some of our early family life.
But my father, after he joined Mrs. Adams in this business that I run today and I'm the principal owner of, he was an outstanding salesman.
He could absolutely sell, I think he could sell bikinis at the North Pole
sell fur coats in Panama.
He was terrific and had a very, very wide acquaintance and following in the Southwest, the whole Southwest.
What kind of man was he, besides being a good salesman?
He was a big guy, a very happy individual, and made friends very, very easily.
Well, I think he was a pretty good guy, really.
And it's been a real pleasure to me since coming back to Texas to occasionally meet someone that knew him and the nice things they say about him.
So it's a pretty good legacy to have people tell you what a nice guy your dad was and so forth.
So I really, I guess in the last 10 years,
I've grown fonder of him than I think I was prior to that time.
He passed away in 67.
No, I'm sorry.
He passed away in 66.
That was before I retired.
And I was on a trip.
I had seen him about two months before.
And then I was on a trip.
I was in San Francisco when I learned of his death and I flew directly into here.
Can you tell me about your mother?
My mother was a very, very nice person, very good person.
She was a generous person.
She had a lot of, a lot of Germanic characteristics and
was a very strict disciplinarian.
I guess that's her Prussian heritage.
Was she from the Prussian area?
Well, she was born in this country and born, matter of fact, born in Fort Worth.
But her mother...
But her mother was from the Prussian area?
Yeah, they very definitely, her mother, quite a story behind her mother's family.
And her father came from Bingen on the Rhine River.
And he was a tradesman.
His whole family were tradesmen.
I think they were brickmakers in Germany, or makers of tile and brick in Germany.
Her mother's family was from East Prussia.

the eastern part of Prussia, and her mother's mother, which would be my mother's grandmother, was actually, it was reported, and I don't know this for a fact, but just from things that I remember my mother's mother saying, and I used to, she lived with us in the last years of her life, and she spoke
native tongue.
And she and her husband formed a German church here in Fort Worth.
A congregational German church.
And during the First World War, they had to stop having services because of so much German, anti-German feeling.
And after World War I, they resumed the German services in the church once a month.
And I
They say that I spoke German before I spoke English.
I spoke German when I was three or four years old.
I don't really have a conscious recollection of speaking German, but they say I spoke German when I was three or four years old.
And then way back in my subconscious was this child of three or four years old vocabulary of German.
understanding or a knowledge of it and I know in my some of my brief usages and opportunity to use it in Germany during the war in asking directions and so
in German, if it was very simple that a child would know or know about, I would understand it.
Or if they spoke very fast, I couldn't get any of it.
And I would always say to them, ,, speak more slowly, please.
And I would understand what a child of four years old might understand.
that was made very, very, very noticeable to me.
Let's stop here for now.
Could you tell me about about your parents a little bit more specifically?
Were they religious people?
Who was the authority in the household?
Could you tell me about that?
I would say that my mother was the authority in the household.
Now, they were of average
following and belief.
We went to church regularly.
I grew up going to Sunday school and so forth.
But they weren't devoutly religious.
Were they interested in politics?
No, no.
My father was not interested in politics and neither was my mother.
Did they vote usually for one party versus another?
Yes, they usually voted, primarily voted
I believe Democratic, but quite often voted Republican for the man, for the individual.
Would you, did you consider them either conservatives or liberals or moderates?
Conservatives, definitely conservatives, yeah.
Now you became a general and throughout your career, what do you think, what
What contribution do you think that your parents made in your future success?
A sense of integrity and honesty.
And I think doing a little bit more than it was expected of you.
To me, extra effort.
is the number one characteristic that I believe would help almost anybody do a job better than the PAC.
And it's something that often some of your peers may say that, well, you're a brown noser
It's just having a sense of belonging or a sense of owning and trying to do a job and not being a perfectionist because we're all subject to human faculties and making mistakes.
But I think if you put forth extra effort and I know my dad was always enthusiastic about everything.
And I've always had that characteristic too.
And I think enthusiasm and extra effort are the two greatest characteristics that a human can have.
Let's start in about your education.
Where'd you go to school?
I went to the primary schools here in Fort Worth and to high school.
So you had a public education?
Public education all the way.
No private education.
education at all.
I was a good student, a very good student.
One of the top in the class?
It was easy for me.
Yes, I would say I was in grade schools and high school.
I was in the top 3% of the class.
I didn't do that well at A&M.
I don't really know why.
I never really thought about it.
I had a lot of outside activities.
I worked hard at football.
I was not an athlete.
I had very little natural athletic ability.
I know Matty Bell told me, he said I had less native ability as a football player than any player he ever saw.
But I played nine months out of the year down at school.
I played intramural and then spring training.
And so I worked real hard because I wanted to be a good football player.
And I did make one letter, finally.
Did you play high school football or any other sports?
I played high school football, yeah.
Did you play other sports in high school?
Baseball.
And I played baseball on the freshman team at A&M.
And the coach, I forget the bastard's name, but in one of the inter-squad games, I struck out.
I was the first baseman, and I loved playing baseball.
And I struck out, and that bastard cut me off of the squad and just broke my heart.
And they had no damn reason.
I was better first baseman than the guy he kept, a big, tall guy from McKinney, Texas.
But that really was a blow to me when that guy cut me off of the fish baseball team at A&M.
I didn't go out for freshman football at A&M because I just didn't think I was good enough.
So I played intramural football on the second battalion artillery team and did real well.
Made two, three touchdowns.
That was in the end.
And of course the coaches all watched the intramural games for potential.
So lo and behold, as a result of the intramural, why they asked me to come out for the varsity in the fall, which I did, which I thought was a big honor.
No kidding.
And the only course I ever busted anywhere, the only course I ever failed,
was at A&M in strength of materials by Professor Long, C.D.
Long, who was in my class.
His brother was a professor in the M.E.
department.
And I think that he and I got cross ways.
I don't think I really busted a chord.
I think he busted me because he felt that I hadn't put forth
the effort that I should have or that I could have, and then I, that I didn't show the potential that I should.
That's the only course I ever busted.
Were you popular in high school?
Yeah, fairly popular.
Were you a leader?
Were you a leader of any organizations?
I'm always wondering when generals, who of course have positions of leadership, started to become leaders.
Yeah, I was a leader of, we had
Oh, several clubs.
Then during the grade school years and early high school years, we were pretty strong here in Fort Worth in calisthenics.
And you know, they don't do that anymore, but I remember we used to, every day, the class or two or three classes get together, the gym classes would, and go through a
routine of sort of drill calisthenics.
And he even had a long rod, kind of like a curtain rod, that we'd used.
All sorts of shapes and routines.
And I was, I was picked as a leader several times in those, for those things.
But I was not a joiner.
I didn't join a lot of things in a lot of clubs, because I
and I never had a whole lot of money.
Our family was never, never destitute.
We were never, you know, overly flushed with money.
My father made a I guess a better than average salary when he worked in the early days in industrial supply as a as a salesman and later as a sales manager for a company here in Fort Warren.
But
Well, I wouldn't say I was any hot shot leader in school.
No, not particularly.
Why were you popular?
Why was I popular?
I didn't have any enemies, per se.
I wasn't prejudiced against and didn't really go out of my way to harass anybody.
I was just trying to be a pretty good guy.
And I was fairly popular with the gals, not extremely popular, but I had a lot of girlfriends.
When you graduated from high school, is that about 1929 or 1930?
Yeah, 1929.
When you graduated from high school, did you have a firm set of aims?
Did you know what you wanted to do?
Yeah, I sure did.
I wanted to be a petroleum engineer and that's what I wanted to do.
Well no, first I wanted to be an army aviator.
Oh really?
And I had applied.
So is that the first time that you ever thought about the military?
I guess so.
Randolph Field to be admitted to Randolph.
In those days it was Randolph for primary and Kelly for the secondary.
So my senior year in the spring I had made application and I was ordered down to Galveston.
There was a little Army Air Corps base at Galveston and a board convened down there

to examine the candidates for the Army Air Corps and about 15 of us went down from A&M down to Galveston and went before the board and physical exams and so forth and I passed everything except the physical and they said that I had eye fatigue and that someday I would have to wear glasses and
They didn't think that I could do, you know, precision flying and so forth and so on.
So, that was a real big disappointment to me.
And before that though, I had already learned to fly.
Oh really?
Yeah, because one year for my junior year in this
for the half year, for the second, in 1932.
See, I started out with a class of 33, but I finished up with a class of 34 because I dropped out half a year.
I had an illness.
I guess I was overworked or something.
I just fell apart.
I don't know if it was mono or what the hell.
But before the end of this, I had,
for the second half in 32, but just a few days before I would have lost credit or given a D for everything, I dropped out of school.
I thought it was the best, and the doctors thought it was the best.
So I dropped out, and I came home, and I went to work over here in this business for Mr. Adams.
He hadn't passed away yet.
And I worked out in the shop making cup leathers.
See, we actually have two businesses here.
We're a little manufacturing business that we carry on, and we're a gasket cutter as well.
And then we are manufacturer's reps, where we represent manufacturers in the Southwest.
In the last few years, I've started a little oil company in addition.
We've got actually three businesses going out here now.
But anyway, I worked over here.
And I got started going out to Meacham Field.
And taking flying lessons.
And I soloed.
And I worked for a guy out there that had a little flying school.
He had Richie.
I'd work for him in the afternoon for three or four hours.
And instead of taking pay, I'd take it out in flying time.
and he'd give me maybe 15 or 20 minutes of instruction for three or four hours of work.
And I'd service the airplanes for him, little Arrancas and little Curtis Robins.
So I learned to fly and I had all, at the time we took the exam for Randolph, I had about 75 hours I guess of time.
So you were about a junior then at A&M when you took the exam?
Yeah, yeah.
And so that was a big, big blow to me.
But after I graduated that summer,
division office out in Crane, Texas, out in West Texas.
Well before we get to that, let's go back, let's go back a little bit.
In other words, the Depression didn't hurt your family that much.
Not at all, not at all.
We, the Depression didn't hurt our family at all.
My father was gainfully employed all during the Depression and
we certainly never, never suffered at all in the Depression.
I think my dad, there was a bank failure here in Fort Worth.
A couple of banks failed.
One of them failed.
He had a checking account and a small savings account in it.
As far as I know, that was the only severe monetary setback as a result of the Depression.
And then, too,
During the early 30s, I was down at A&M.
Sure.
We didn't really, I didn't really suffer then.
I did a lot of work.
I worked in the mess hall.
And I had the midnight mail concession for a while.
You know what the midnight mail is?
No.
Well, I don't know where they still- Oh, is that the train coming by?
I don't know if they still do that or not.
In those days, it finally became a football and I got it kind of a quasi football job.
But in each dormitory, and we had about 14 of them in those days, 12 I guess counting them.
Yeah, some of them are torn down now.
But anyway, we had a mailbox in each one of these dormitories.
And guys, alongside this box was another little box with half envelopes.

So if during the night you wanted to get off a letter and be sure it got out that night and you wrote it, say, after supper, you could take your letter with a stamp on it, put it in one of those half envelopes, drop a nickel in the half envelope, and then drop it in the box, the midnight mail box.
And about 11.30

went around, opened all those boxes up, took the nickels they had, and go down to the railroad station, and we mailed them on the train, on the OWL, the train out of Houston towards Dallas, Fort Worth.
And mailed all of them on that eastbound train, on that northbound train.
And then that northbound train sorted the mail and inhearned anything that was for Houston
and southbound traffic, they put it off of that train and gave it to the southbound train, which they met up with in Heard.
And that was called a midnight mail.
So you collected nickels then?
The first year I had that, I did it myself every night.
And collect those nickels.
And every night you'd get, oh 20, 25, or 30,
or before a big football game or something, hell you might get 50 or 60 nickels.
Two, three, or four dollars.
And a couple of nights raining real hard.
Instead of walking down the railroad station, I mailed them in the Y.
But it was quite a, quite a little deal.
And then next year,
And I gave him a guaranteed a dollar a night just to go get the mail and take it down and mail it.
It was a good deal for him.
It was a good deal for me.
I trusted him.
But no, the depression never really, you know, we didn't suffer.
We had a lot of fun.
Many times I hitchhiked to Houston with 50 cents in my pocket.
Now, when you went to A&M, did you already make up your mind that you want to be a patrolling engineer, and is that why you went?
Yes and no.
It's really quite strange.
I had wanted to go to A&M.
Why?
But the summer, I liked the military, and I'd seen the Corps trips come up here and the guys parading and everything.
him by his tails.
He had been a first sergeant and a cavalry troop from Pennsylvania volunteers that saw duty after the Civil War even in Texas out in Fort Concho in San Angelo.
So I was pretty much wanted to go to a military school, but after I got out of high school one of my relatives, a relative of
was one of the big wheels out of Texas Tech.
And he wanted me to come out there and said I would get a scholarship and get a job and everything.
So I reluctantly went
And I got a job and they were going to give me a partial scholarship and I got a job working in either a Piggly Wiggly or Safeway or one of the supermarkets.
Found a place to live temporarily until the dormitories opened and I was really set up.
Real, real good.
And the lady that I had a room with had a couple of daughters my age and they were in
age.
But some sand started to set in and the sand got to blowing and goddamn it blew for days and days and I said to hell with this noise I'm going to A&M.
So I quit my job got on the damn train with my trunks and I went to College Station passed through Fort Worth never called my folks or anything

got off of the damn train at College Station, and one of the night sergeants was down there, and I think it was about seven or eight o'clock in the evening, and he said, you're a little early, it was about three weeks before school started, and I told him, I said, well, I'm coming, I just came in from Lovell, and he said, well, you can't spend the night down here, he said,
come on, put your bag up on this dolly.
You know, one of those express wagons, big four-wheel wagons.
And he said, I'll help you pull it up here.
And we pulled it up the street there, and he stopped over by Law and Pervier Hall.
And he said, let's throw your trunk off here.
He says, you take the wagon back to the station.
And...
by the time you get back I'll have a key and I'll let you, I'll put you in one of these rooms here in the first stoop of law, I guess it was.
So I did, I pulled a goddamn wagon back down to the station and he wanted to know if I'd eaten and I said no.
He said well, he said the only thing that's open is a little store down here and he showed me where that was and you can go down there and get a sandwich.
He said, you can stay over here.
He said, there's no sheets or anything, just the beds with mattresses.
But the water's on.
You can stay in there tonight.
He said, tomorrow you go up to the commandant's office and tell them who you are and what you want to do and everything.
So he was a real nice guy.
I saw him many times after that.
I don't remember his name.
But he was kind of an elderly gentleman, a real kind fellow.
So he really got me started off in great fashion.
And the next morning, I had no trouble that night.
He opened the door for me and everything.
Next morning, bright and early, I was up in the main building there, the old main building.
The Commandant's office before they opened.
I was standing on the outside waiting.
And the Assistant Commandant, the Commandant was a military guy, Nelson, Bull Nelson.
But the assistant commandant was a civilian, Johnny, God, I can't remember his name.
But of all the things, he knew my father.
No kidding.
Yeah.
From some, he met him someplace and had seen him two or three times after that.
So when I was standing there at the door and he unlocked the door and one of the ladies
And then I said, well, come on in.
He said, you're a little early.
So, after I told him my story and everything, well, they were really intrigued with it.
And he said, well, he said, you have any money?
I said, well, I've got a little bit, not a whole lot, but I'd like to get a job.
And he said, well, we'll just see if we can't put you to work doing something.
So, it was about
two weeks before school started.
So he said, we just got from the printers the new house rules that we want everybody to live by.
We've got to have a copy nailed in every room on the campus, nailed on the back of the front door.
There were actually two little cards.
So he said, you can do that.
And he said, you have to go in every room
every room and every dormitory, and nail these on the back of the door.
He said, that'll take you at least a week, I know.
So after you finish that, and he gave me all the stuff and everything, hammer and a little tacks.
So I started in, and hell, in about five days, I was finished.
So they gave me some other jobs to do.
So anyway, to make a long story short, I worked.
And before registration, he let me register early and everything.
And they paid me 70 cents an hour, I believe.
70 cents?
Yeah.
That's fantastic.
Yeah.
That's a lot of money with a minimum wage of 25 cents.
Sure was.
Sure was.
Paid me 70 cents an hour for going around tacking up all of those cards and all the rooms and everything.
So that was enough to, you know, to pay for my food and everything.
A few days there.
What outfit were you put in in the Corps?
F-Artillery.
And it was a, I was a charter member because they just organized it that year.
And it, I, you know, it was a real, real good start and a real good experience.
By luck, the good Lord had his arms around me that Johnny, it wasn't Johnny Mitchell, no, I'll think of it, I'll recall it here in a minute.
Anyway, he, you know, the fact that he knew, knew my father and knew my family was bound to have helped in some way.
If I'd have been a total cold stranger, I might not have gotten the consideration and everything that I did.
But I was, my mind was pretty much made up that if I couldn't be a military aviator that I wanted to go ahead and work and be a petroleum engineer.
And I never changed from that and I had a kind of a fallback that if I didn't go the petroleum end of it that I'd be a chemical engineer.
And the first
But after my sophomore year with geology, historical geology, and a couple of the professors that I had, I was definitely sold that I wanted to be a patrol engineer.
What did you like about the Corps of Cadets?
What did I like about it?
I guess I liked the military routine.
I liked the idea in those days that, you know, we had formations for meals.
And I would always get a big charge in the evenings at retreat.
We'd just stay in retreat and march to the mess hall.
And later, when I was working in the mess hall and waiting tables on the training table, well of course I wasn't in formation, I'd walk down

ahead of time and after I went out my junior and senior year when I was waiting on a training table I never really did anything just all I had to do was carry a white jacket and but I guess you know it's not corny I like the military routine
And I got a charge out of stand and retreat and everything.
Did you like the hazing?
No, I didn't.
And I thought that was, to me that was I think one of the foolish childish things about A&M in the early days.
It was a falsified macho syndrome that I think that
a lot of people latched on to.

I know in our organization and in my freshman class we had a couple of guys that I knew were going to be just real horses asses when they became sophomores as far as the hazing is concerned and they both
He was dead.
He died in the war, died on Bataan.
Kid from Dallas named George Brundrett.
Heck of a nice guy.
He was my roommate for a few months.
But he was killed in one of those prisoner of war ships that we torpedoed unknowingly.
The Japs were transporting some of our prisoners from the Philippines back to Japan.
and the ship was torpedoed by one of our own submarines.
George was on one of them.
No, I think the hazing was not a good thing.
I don't think it really hurt anybody, but it certainly didn't do anybody any good.
What were some other things about the Corps that you disliked?
Oh, I don't, I don't guess there's anything significantly that I dislike per se.
In what way do you think that the Corps helped you in your military career, or is there any way that it might have hindered your career?
I think it definitely helped it.
I think that our, our, that the, that the military program and the military

the situation at A&M in those days, the Corps in those days, particularly in the military science courses that we pursued after the second two years, after the first two years, made us superior officers in our particular branches.
In other words, I was field artillery.
And I know the year that we graduated, we went to summer camp that year directly.
We graduated and had final review.
And I think the next morning, we were to report at Fort St. Houston.
A bunch of us were.
They gave us the option of going later in the summer.
And I said, well, I don't have a job yet.
Don't have to report till September.
So we just went directly to camp.
And I know down in Fort Sam, we went out on the firing range at Bullis and firing some problems, some artillery problems out there.
Numerous times, we would be at the observation point and there'd be some graduates from the current class at West Point also there.
There was a bunch of them.
They were out there and they were trying to fire a problem and losing every round and not knowing where in the hell we were and the regular army officers would have one of us take over.
And we were far superior to all of them in the particular technique and knowledge of our particular branch.
Of course, they were a little better overall because
They certainly had more and more concentrated, but in each particular branch, the graduate from Texas A&M was superior to the graduate of the military academy.
Now, why were they a little bit better overall?
They were a little bit better overall because they covered other curriculum in the military that we didn't particularly cover in A&M.
better drill and formality and military law and all this sort of stuff.

But in the pick and shovel nut and bolts of the artillery or the field artillery or coast artillery or even infantry officer, the graduate's man knew more about the tactical application of his particular branch

than did the graduate of the military academy and I've had regular army tactical officers tell me that and I know later during the war some of my peers that were west pointers you know they were they'd look down their nose at you and not in a in an outward way but in an inward way
The biggest feeling you get from that in the military was in the wives of West Pointers.
Really?
In their relationship with the wives of, we'll say, an A&M man.
An officer from A&M.
Yeah, some of the snippy little things with just, you know, my husband's a West Pointer and your husband was an ROTC officer and so forth.
And most of the West Pointers, they pressed too hard.
I have had a lot of good friends from the military academy in the service.
Really, I can truthfully say I don't, am not conscious of any
prejudice that they directed specifically towards me in any way because I was not a member, was not from the military academy.
But there certainly was a lot of it and it was always present.
But I always tried to feel like that, you know, we could hold our own against anything they could do.
And I know and
when it came out and it was an actual fact that Texas A&M furnished more officers for the military than did the military academy in World War II.
This is an actual, there was some Aggie that was in the A.G.
